The paper focuses on analyzing the security and privacy implications of third-party services embedded in websites, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) and web technologies (cs.WEB). The paper also uses a model called "third party trees" to measure the dependencies of third-party services, which could fall under the category of data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses legal frameworks related to third-party services, which could fall under the category of cyberlaw (cs.CY). Finally, the paper uses large-scale measurement studies to analyze the data, which could fall under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
